**Description**

Certain ways of expressing colors — hexadecimal and CSS strings — can safely be assumed to be in the sRGB color space. Hexadecimal syntax implies sRGB by convention, and CSS colors are _always_ sRGB except where otherwise specified in the (very recent) CSS Color Module Level 4.

However, colors passed to three.js shader must be Linear-sRGB. Because hexadecimal and CSS colors are not (by convention or specification) in the required color space, I believe we should take the step of converting them from sRGB to Linear-sRGB on the user's behalf. Importantly, this ensures that hexadecimal colors from a color picker, or CSS colors from a stylesheet, can be used directly in three.js APIs. They will appear correctly without manual conversion, assuming `.outputEncoding = sRGBEncoding` is also set.

The changes provided by this PR are disabled by default (`ColorManagement.legacyMode = true`), but can be enabled by default (in a future release) at the same time as we change the default value of `renderer.outputEncoding` to `sRGBEncoding`, minimizing impact of the output encoding change on the remaining users who haven't yet enabled it.

```js
// current defaults
THREE.ColorManagement.legacyMode = true;
renderer.outputEncoding = LinearEncoding;

// future defaults
THREE.ColorManagement.legacyMode = false;
renderer.outputEncoding = sRGBEncoding;
```

As discussed in https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/issues/23614, `.outputEncoding` should perhaps also be renamed to `.outputColorSpace` at this time.

RGB and HSL components (e.g. `color.r`) continue to be Linear-sRGB ("Linear"), and can be manipulated exactly as before. I understand this may seem like an inconsistency, but it's exactly how Blender's color picker works as well, and ensures that lerping and keyframe animation continue to execute in Linear-sRGB color space.

```js
// No change for RGB or HSL input.
color.r = color.g = color.b = 0.5;
color.setRGB( 0.5, 0.5, 0.5 );
color.setHSL( 0.0, 1.0, 0.5 );
console.log( color.r ); // → 0.5

// CSS input is sRGB by specification, and converted to Linear-sRGB by this PR.
color.setStyle( 'rgb( 127 127 127 )' );
console.log( color.r ); // → 0.214041140

// Hex input is sRGB by convention, and converted to Linear-sRGB by this PR.
color.setHex( 0x808080 );
console.log( color.r ); // → 0.214041140

// Default input color space can be overridden.
color.setStyle( 'rgb( 127 127 127 )', LinearSRGBColorSpace );
color.setHex( 0x808080, LinearSRGBColorSpace );
console.log( color.r ); // → 0.5
```

**Changes**

- Add `SRGBColorSpace` and `LinearSRGBColorSpace` enums
- Add `colorSpace` argument to THREE.Color getters/setters
    - Hexadecimal and CSS input are considered sRGB by default
    - All other inputs are considered Linear-sRGB by default
    - sRGB input will be converted to Linear-sRGB, as required by the renderer
- Add `ColorManagement` API. Only its `.legacyMode` flag is intended as a public API at this time. Other methods or properties may be added to support wide-gamut workflows in the future.

**Effects**

- Frameworks like A-Frame and R3F already enable color management as a layer on top of three.js, treating user-provided colors as sRGB by default. These changes allow vanilla three.js users to provide colors in the same way.
- Many examples already use `renderer.outputEncoding=sRGB`, and so hard-coded colors (like background and ground colors) are implicitly Linear-sRGB... These will need to be updated (or their appearance will change) with color management enabled.
- Fog and background color are excluded from output encoding. As a result, the two lines below result in different colors, and that doesn't seem ideal:
    - `basicMaterial.color.setHex( ..., sRGBColorSpace )`
    - `background.setHex( ..., sRGBColorSpace )`

**Next steps**

An upcoming PR will add documentation explaining what is meant by "working color space", and how that relates to choices of input and output color spaces. That documentation is meant to be a significantly expanded version of the content at https://www.donmccurdy.com/2020/06/17/color-management-in-threejs/.

